Git commands: add, commit and push are graduating steps for adding a new file to the remote repository.

The first step is add, which add changes to the working directory and put them on a stage.
We can add all the changes using “add . “ or desired files giving the full path of the file.

The second step is commit, which we use to confirm all the changes. It takes all the files from the stage
and saves their state in time. The commit has a pointer to the object with the content of a stage.
We need to add a description to the commit using “-m <some text>”.

The last, third step is a push, which sends the update to the remote repository with all the commits previously made.
We can give the name of the branch form which we made changes, by default it’s main
